When were talking about a real person, I dont think its possible to over react.  If it was about a stolen car, robbed bank, ect then I would maybe see your point.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  From a practical standpoint, would dying to save my child be better or worse for <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
blah blah.  I'm not going to sit around and say it would be &quot;Better&quot; for anyone.  You or a child dying would be a horrible, tragic thing.  If I was your wife and was forced to choose between the two deaths, I would hope you had your things in order.  In my eyes it would be heroic to lose your life to save your childs.  Everyone dies, at least that death would have given a child the chance at life.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  There's just too much emotion out there regarding the issue of children and their safety, and that's what I'm trying to attack here. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm sitting here trying to comprehend this statement, and for the life of me I just cant understand it.  Look around, watch the news, pick up a paper.  Until we live in a perfect world, where children aren't at risk for the numerous dangers in society, there isn't enough emotion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The fundamental question has not been answered: what does it mean to put a child first? How much is enough? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm a very passionate and emotional person.  The question how much is enough, could never be answered from me. Every day when I look in my childrens faces, the answer is nothing is to much.  I'm not talking about the best toys, and most expensive clothes.  I'm simply saying the day will never come where my needs superseed theirs.  <br>
<br>
Their health, food, clothing, personal needs will always come before mine.  If ever a day comes when I cant provide for them, I wouldnt be able to put a limit on what I would do so they were cared for.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Overprotectiveness <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I really dont like that word.  There really isn't a general standard for this word.  I am probably considered as an overprotective parent, but I'm not obsessed with it.  My children know the rules, and understand why they are in place.  <br>
<br>
They dont spend the night at friends houses, but their friends are more then welcome to here.  Double standard?  Maybe so.  I know whats not (guns) in my house, and more importantly what is.  I have no way of knowing if there are guns in their friends houses, or if their friends have been tought proper gun safety.  My children play outside, but only when our property is secured. They get dropped off, and picked up from school.  They dont ride school busses, and they dont have to wait at bus stops, or walk unattended.  <br>
<br>
Accidents do happen, even with overprotected children.  You can't prevent everything, but I do my best  to try and prevent them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Thanks Celdor for the non emotional reply. Like I said, I won't win this discussion, because people just get mad and holier than thou about children. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
When the discussion is children, or negligent parents you wont get an emotionless post from me. If you dont like it, dont read it.<br>
<br>
Foof<br>
