shame on some of you. To make light of this whole thread with your tasteless jokes and posts is quite disgusting. I am sure the family of the children that died would find great comfort in your humor (or lack thereof).<br>
<br>
I closed my eyes for a moment when I read the story and the first vision I saw was what I could only imagine these babies looked like and experienced. Thier little faces all red and sweaty, probably not crying thinking mommy would be back soon. Then the pain sets in and they start feeling sick, vomiting uncontrollably all over themselves ... and then the crying starts ... and the panic sets in. They slowly drift off, probably still wimpering.<br>
So, did that not affect you with a lump in your throat and wanting to weep for these babies as they suffered ? I would hope not because that would make you just like her.<br>
One thing that really concerns me is the possible lack of attention by passer-bys. Did no one notice these children in the car as it sat in front of a salon ? Is it possible she is the only customer this place had all day? I have reported people in the Wal-Mart parking lot for leaving their sleeping children in car seats in the back.<br>
As for driving around for 3 hours I am sure she was pretty stunned when reality kicked her in the teeth as she came back to see them dead. The horror she felt as she realized someone would know she killed them and what consequences lay ahead for her. You think in 3 hours she could have come up with a better lie.<br>
I am not going to sit here and argue the points of finer parenting. I am a single parent of 4 wonderful children and will NEVER pretend that I am the perfect parent. One thing I can say is that I could never possibly concieve how a mother could do this to her own children, even out of sheer stupidity and selfishness. <br>
Try explaining to the baby she carries that it's mother is the reason it will never know it's siblings.<br>
<br>
As a side note : Who is to say that "smart" people will not create "stupid" children ?<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukamakasibattlemaster.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kamakasi Battlemaster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 422<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/11/02 6:50:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3449.topic&index=53>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Latest News Update</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Mom Who Left Kids Faces Manslaughter Charges<br>
<br>
Tarajee Maynor Had Third Child<br>
<br>
Posted: 8:05 a.m. EDT July 10, 2002<br>
Updated: 1:01 a.m. EDT July 11, 2002<br>
<br>
SOUTHFIELD, Mich.-- A woman accused of leaving her two children to die inside a hot car last week is being ordered to stand trial on an involuntary manslaughter charge and not the original charge of murder, Local 4 learned. <br>
 <br>
Tarajee Shaheer Maynor, 25, was originally charged with two counts of felony murder. Judge Steven Cooper of the 46th District Court said that there was not enough evidence to prove that Maynor intentionally killed her children, Local 4 reported. <br>
<br>
Prosecutors want Maynor charged with two counts of first-degree murder. They said that Maynor knowingly left her 3-year-old son and 10-month-old daughter inside a locked car for more than three hours while shopping for clothes, receiving a massage, and getting her hair done at a Southfield salon on June 28. They said that she disregarded the consequences of her actions that day, as temperatures reached into the 80s. <br>
<br>
A detective who interviewed Maynor when she took the children to the hospital said that Maynor made a statement to him and confessed to neglecting her children. She reportedly told him &quot;I would never hurt my children. I was too stupid to know they would die.&quot; <br>
<br>
Defense Attorney Albert Hatchett said that he was pleased with the judge's ruling. <br>
<br>
&quot;Satisfied that the judge took serious note of it,&quot; Hatchett said. &quot;And plus there is a complete absence of any evidence to the contrary.&quot; <br>
<br>
The children reportedly died from hyperthermia after being in the car for about three hours in the sweltering heat. Temperatures in the car reportedly topped 100 degrees and the children likely survived only 20 to 40 minutes, Local 4 reported. <br>
<br>
Maynor drove around three hours with the dead children in her car before taking them to the hospital, Southfield police said. Once at the hospital, she reportedly told investigators that she had been abducted and raped, Local 4 reported. <br>
<br>
Investigators said that the evidence and her story did not match, and began to interview her further. Police said that she eventually confessed to leaving the children inside the car. She reportedly told police that she was trying to figure out what to do as she drove around for three hours after discovering they had died. <br>
<br>
The children were covered with vomit when they were taken to Providence Hospital by their mother, Local 4 reported. Lip marks were found on the car window, suggesting that the 3-year-old was gasping for air, the station reported. The boy also reportedly removed his sister from her car seat in what would appear to be an attempt to help her. <br>
<br>
A judge allowed Maynor to see the children at a private viewing Friday at the James Cole Home For Funerals. <br>
<br>
Oakland County Prosecutor David Gorcyca said that he would continue to seek murder charges. He claims that Maynor intentionally parked her car in the back of the parking lot in an effort to conceal the fact that the children were inside. <br>
<br>
Local 4 has learned that Maynor had a third child. Gorcyca said that she walked into an unnamed Wayne County facility and said that she no longer wanted the child before leaving it there for 58 days. The child was eventually put up for adoption. <br>
<br>
Prosecutors say Maynor is a mother who felt burdened by her children, Local 4 reported. The child she gave up was born some time between her son and daughter who died. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
